{{Infobox UK legislation | short_title = Budget Responsibility and National Audit Act 2011 | parliament = Parliament of the United Kingdom | long_title = {{hide||An Act to make provision for a Charter for Budget Responsibility and for the publication of Financial Statements and Budget Reports; to establish the Office for Budget Responsibility; to make provision about the Comptroller and Auditor General and to establish a body corporate called the National Audit Office; to amend Schedules 5 and 7 to the Government of Wales Act 2006 in relation to the Auditor General for Wales; and for connected purposes.}} | statute_book_chapter = 2011 c 4 | introduced_by = [[James Sassoon, Baron Sassoon|Lord Sassoon]] | territorial_extent = England and Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland | royal_assent = {{Start date|2011|03|22|df=y}} | commencement = 23 March 2011; 4 April 2011<ref>[http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2011/892/made/data.pdf The Budget Responsibility and National Audit Act 2011 (Commencement No.1) Order 2011 SI 2011/892]</ref> | repeal_date = | amendments = | related_legislation = [[Fiscal Responsibility Act 2010]] | repealing_legislation = | status = Current | original_text = http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2011/04/enacted?view=plain | activeTextDocId = | legislation_history = http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2010-11/budgetresponsibilityandnationalaudithl.html | use_new_UK-LEG = yes | revised_text = | theyworkforyou = Budget Responsibility and National Audit Act 2011 }}
The '''Budget Responsibility and National Audit Act 2011''' (c. 4) is an [[Act of Parliament|Act]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. It provides a statutory footing for the already-established [[Office for Budget Responsibility]], and requires the treasury to set out its approach to fiscal policy in a Charter for Budget Responsibility. It also sets out a new structure for the [[National Audit Office (United Kingdom)|National Audit Office]] and repeals the [[Fiscal Responsibility Act 2010]].
It was introduced in the [[House of Lords]] by the [[Commercial Secretary to the Treasury]] [[James Sassoon, Baron Sassoon|Lord Sassoon]], on behalf of the [[Cameron–Clegg coalition|Government]], and it received [[Royal Assent]] on 22 March 2011.
== Office for Budget Responsibility == {{Main|Office for Budget Responsibility}} The Office for Budget Responsibility was initially constituted in shadow form by the Conservative party opposition in December 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=Conservatives launch Office for Budget Responsibility|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8401517.stm|publisher=[[BBC News website]]|accessdate=2011-04-29|date=2009-12-08}}</ref> It was then formally created by the new government after the [[United Kingdom general election, 2010|general election]] in May 2010, before being put on a statutory footing by this Act.
The OBR provides independent [[economic forecast]]s as background to the preparation of the [[United Kingdom budget|UK budget]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Osborne to give details of £6bn spending cuts next week|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/8685989.stm|publisher=[[BBC News website]]|accessdate=2011-04-29|date=2010-05-17}}</ref>
