{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Spokeo, Inc. v. Robins |ArgueDate=November 2 |ArgueYear=2015 |DecideDate=May 16 |DecideYear=2016 |FullName=Spokeo, Inc., Petitioner v. Thomas Robins |USVol=578 |USPage=___ |ParallelCitations= |Docket=13–1339 |OralArgument=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2015/13-1339 |OpinionAnnouncement=https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/15pdf/13-1339-new_4428.pdf |Prior=''finding standing'', {{cite court |vol=742 |reporter=F.3d |opinion= 409|date=2014|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=15051650234664622607}} |Procedural= |Subsequent=''finding standing'', {{cite court||vol=867 |reporter=F.3d |opinion= 1108|date=2017|url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=17482366739814356077}} |Holding=Because the Ninth Circuit failed to consider both the concrete and particularized aspects of the injury-in-fact requirement, its Article III standing analysis was incomplete. |SCOTUS=2016 |Majority=Alito |JoinMajority=Roberts, Kennedy, Thomas, Breyer, Kagan |Concurrence=Thomas |Dissent=Ginsburg |JoinDissent=Sotomayor |Dissent2= |JoinDissent2= |LawsApplied= [[Fair Credit Reporting Act]], 15 U.S.C. § 1681 et seq. }}
'''''Spokeo, Inc. v. Robins''''', 578 U.S. ___ (2016), was a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case in which the Court vacated and [[remand (court procedure)|remanded]] a ruling by [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] on the basis that the Ninth Circuit had not properly determined whether the plaintiff has suffered an "injury-in-fact" when analyzing whether he had [[Standing (law)|standing]] to bring his case in [[Federal judiciary of the United States|federal court]].<ref>''Spokeo, Inc. v. Robins'', No. 13–1339, 578 U.S. ___, slip op. at 8-11 (2016).</ref> The Court did not discuss whether "the Ninth Circuit’s ultimate conclusion — that Robins adequately alleged an injury in fact — was correct."<ref>''Spokeo'', slip op. at 11.</ref>
==Background== [[Spokeo]], Inc. operates a [[.com]] website featuring a "people [[web search engine|search engine]]" with which its users can obtain in-depth consumer reports on individual persons.<ref name=harv1>{{Bluebook journal |first=|last=Note| title=The Supreme Court, 2015 Term — Leading Cases | volume=130 | journal=[[Harvard Law Review|Harv. L. Rev.]] | page=437 | url=http://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/437-446_Online.pdf| year=2016}}.</ref>{{rp|437}}<ref>{{Bluebook journal |first=|last=[[William Baude]]| title=Standing in the Shadow of Congress| volume=2016 | journal=[[Supreme Court Review|S. Ct. Rev.]] | page=197 |url=http://www.journals.uchicago.edu/doi/10.1086/692120| year=2016}}.</ref> In 2010, a [[class action]] law firm sued Spokeo in the [[United States District Court for the Central District of California]], alleging violations of the [[Fair Credit Reporting Act]] (FCRA).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dougherty|first1=Conor|title=Jay Edelson, the Class-Action Lawyer Who May Be Tech’s Least Friended Man|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/04/05/technology/unpopular-in-silicon-valley.html|accessdate=12 February 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=5 April 2015|page=BU1}}</ref> Thomas Robins, the named [[plaintiff]], alleged that he was unemployed while Spokeo's profile of him falsely stated that he worked in a professional field, had a graduate degree, was a married parent, had a high level of wealth, and included a false age and profile photograph.<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|437}} In January 2011, Judge [[Otis D. Wright II]] dismissed the initial [[complaint]] for not alleging "any actual or imminent harm" after which Robins amended his complaint to allege employment, stress and anxiety injuries.<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|438}} In May 2011, Judge Wright found Robins had alleged a valid injury-in-fact before then reversing himself and dismissing the case for lack of [[standing (law)|standing]] after Spokeo filed for an [[appeal]].<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|438}}
In June 2012, Spokeo agreed to pay $800,000 to settle a separate FCRA based lawsuit filed by the [[Federal Trade Commission]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wyatt|first1=Edward|title=Spokeo Is Penalized by F.T.C. in Sale of Personal Data|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/13/technology/ftc-levies-first-fine-over-internet-data.html|accessdate=12 February 2018|work=The New York Times|date=13 June 2012|page=B2}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Spokeo to Pay $800,000 to Settle FTC Charges Company Allegedly Marketed Information to Employers and Recruiters in Violation of FCRA|url=https://www.ftc.gov/news-events/press-releases/2012/06/spokeo-pay-800000-settle-ftc-charges-company-allegedly-marketed|accessdate=12 February 2018|work=[[Federal Trade Commission]]|date=12 June 2012|language=en}}</ref>
In February 2014, a unanimous panel of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] reversed Judge Wright's dismissal and remanded the case.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Robins v. Spokeo, Inc. |vol=742 |reporter=F.3d |opinion= 409|pinpoint= |court=9th Cir. |date=2014 |url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=15051650234664622607|accessdate= |quote=}}</ref> Judge [[Diarmuid O'Scannlain]], joined by Judges [[Susan P. Graber]] and [[Carlos Bea]], reasoned that Robins had alleged injuries sufficient to establish standing because FCRA protected individual, rather than collective, rights and Robins was suing for a violation of his own statutory rights.<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|438}} In a footnote, the Circuit explicitly found it did not need to reach Robins' additional allegations regarding injuries to his employment prospects or from anxiety.<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|439}}
The [[Supreme Court of the United States]] granted Spokeo's petition for a writ of [[certiorari]] and one-hour of [[oral argument]]s were heard on November 2, 2015, where Deputy [[Solicitor General of the United States|U.S. Solicitor General]] Malcom Stewart appeared for the government as a friend in support of Robins.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liptak|first1=Adam|authorlink=Adam Liptak|title=Justices Hear Debate on Suing Companies for Seemingly Harmless Falsehoods|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/03/business/justices-hear-debate-on-suing-companies-for-seemingly-harmless-falsehoods.html|accessdate=12 February 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=3 November 2015|page=B3}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=The Editorial Board|title=Opinion: Justices Should Let an Online Privacy Case Proceed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/01/opinion/sunday/justices-should-let-a-online-privacy-case-proceed.html|accessdate=12 February 2018|work=The New York Times|date=1 November 2015|page=SR10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Spokeo, Inc. v. Robins|url=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2015/13-1339|website=[[Oyez Project]]|accessdate=12 February 2018}}</ref>
==Opinion of the Court== On May 16, 2016, the Supreme Court delivered judgment in favor of Spokeo, [[vacated judgment|vacating]] and [[remand (court procedure)|remanding]] by a vote of 6-2.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liptak|first1=Adam|title=Supreme Court Returns False-Data Case to Appeals Panel|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/05/17/business/supreme-court-returns-false-data-case-to-appeals-panel.html|accessdate=12 February 2018|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=17 May 2016|page=B3}}</ref> Justice [[Samuel Alito]], joined by Chief Justice [[John Roberts]], as well as Justices [[Anthony Kennedy]], [[Clarence Thomas]], [[Stephen Breyer]], and [[Elena Kagan]], wrote that the circuit below had failed to establish that Robins had [[standing (law)|standing]] to file the lawsuit under [[Article Three of the United States Constitution]].<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|439}}
The Court first explained that the Constitution's [[Case or Controversy Clause]] requires any plaintiff to allege an injury-in-fact that is "concrete and particularized".<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|439}} While the Ninth Circuit identified particular harms to Robins, it erred, according to the Court, by not also determining that those harms were "concrete".<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|439}} Although intangible harms such as [[risk]] can be concrete, the Court clarified, "bare procedural violations" cannot.<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|439}} The Court remanded the case while taking "no position as to whether the Ninth Circuit’s ultimate conclusion— that Robins adequately alleged an injury in fact— was correct."<ref>''Spokeo, Inc. v. Robins'', 136 S. Ct. 1540, 1550 (2015).</ref>
===Justice Thomas' concurrence=== Justice [[Clarence Thomas]] added a concurrence, alone.<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|440}} He wrote separately to describe his belief that the Constitution's Case or Controversy requirement is founded upon the [[common law]] distinction between [[private rights]] and [[public rights]] as articulated by [[William Blackstone]].<ref>''Spokeo, Inc. v. Robins'', 136 S. Ct. 1540, 1551 (2015) (Thomas, J., concurring), citing [http://www.law.virginia.edu/pdf/faculty/hein/woolhandler/102mich_l_rev689_2004.pdf Woolhander & Nelson, ''Does History Defeat Standing Doctrine?''], 102 Mich. L. Rev. 689, 693 (2004).</ref>
===Justice Ginsburg's dissent=== Justice [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]], joined by [[Sonia Sotomayor]], dissented.<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|441}} Justice Ginsburg wrote that she agreed with much of the Court’s opinion but saw "no utility" in remanding the case back to the Ninth Circuit. Justice Ginsburg saw the many inaccuracies published by Spokeo as concretely harming Robins and, as such, she would have simply affirmed.<ref name=harv1/>{{rp|441}}
==Subsequent developments== On August 15, 2017, the Ninth Circuit again allowed Robins' lawsuit to proceed.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Robins v. Spokeo, Inc. |vol=867 |reporter=F.3d |opinion= 1108|pinpoint= |court=9th Cir. |date=2017 |url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=17482366739814356077|accessdate= |quote=}}</ref><ref name=harv2>{{Bluebook journal |first=|last=Note| title=Recent Case: Ninth Circuit Allows Fair Credit Reporting Act Class Action to Proceed Past Standing Challenge| volume=131 | journal=Harv. L. Rev. | page=894 | url=https://harvardlawreview.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/894-901_Online.pdf| year=2018}}.</ref>{{rp|894}} Judge O'Scannlain, joined by the same judges as before, now found that Robins had alleged a sufficiently concrete harm to establish an injury in fact under the Constitution. Relying on an ''[[amicus curiae]]'' brief filed by the [[Consumer Financial Protection Bureau]] in support of Robins, Judge O'Scannlain determined that publishing even flattering inaccuracies could harm a job seeker.
